<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,457,613,639]" box="[189,457,613,639]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,457,613,639]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,457,613,639]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[188,1400,660,968]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<taxonomicName authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,399,660,686]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pedi" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,399,660,686]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Ebenacobius pedi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[406,582,661,687]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished by the following combination of features: claws simple, prothorax and elytra similarly pale brown, with two longitudinal dark bands on prothorax not reaching apical margin and glabrous elytra (
<figureCitation box="[735,830,730,756]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1853,1879]" captionTargetBox="[377,1222,265,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-15@20.[349,1238,265,1815]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 3. A–I. Habitus of males of Ebenacobius Haran gen. nov. in dorsal view (part 2). A. E. mulanjensis Haran gen. et sp. nov. B. E. hessei Haran gen. et sp. nov. C. E. pedi Haran gen. et sp. nov. D. E. tsonga Haran gen. et sp. nov. E. E. hippopotamorum Haran gen. et sp. nov. F. E. incognitus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. G. E. oberprieleri Haran gen. et sp. nov. H. E. turneri (Marshall, 1935) gen. et comb. nov. I. E. rhodesianus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6532977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6532977/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
), lacking a visible row of recumbent setae on interstriae. This species shows a peculiar body of penis, regularly widening from base to apex in dorsal view, with the apex truncate (Fig. 6L). This species is very close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[1000,1112,802,827]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tsonga" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1000,1112,802,827]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">E. tsonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1122,1301,801,827]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but the latter species shows distinct rows of setae on interstriae 5–10 of elytra. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[1019,1228,836,862]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pedi">
<emphasis box="[1019,1228,836,862]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Ebenacobius pedi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Haran" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[306,620,871,898]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hippopotamorum" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[306,540,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">E. hippopotamorum</emphasis>
Haran
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[627,802,872,898]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
but in the latter species the scutellar shield and the base of first interstriae is dark brown and the dark bands on prothorax are generally reaching the apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[288,379,941,968]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1853,1879]" captionTargetBox="[377,1222,265,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-15@20.[349,1238,265,1815]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 3. A–I. Habitus of males of Ebenacobius Haran gen. nov. in dorsal view (part 2). A. E. mulanjensis Haran gen. et sp. nov. B. E. hessei Haran gen. et sp. nov. C. E. pedi Haran gen. et sp. nov. D. E. tsonga Haran gen. et sp. nov. E. E. hippopotamorum Haran gen. et sp. nov. F. E. incognitus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. G. E. oberprieleri Haran gen. et sp. nov. H. E. turneri (Marshall, 1935) gen. et comb. nov. I. E. rhodesianus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6532977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6532977/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,324,1007,1033]" box="[189,324,1007,1033]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1007,1033]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1007,1033]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[188,1399,1053,1150]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
This species name is dedicated to the Pedi people, inhabitants of the northern provinces of the 
<collectingCountry name="South Africa" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Republic of South Africa</collectingCountry>
. These peoples share this land with the Tsonga peoples, as do 
<taxonomicName authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[1087,1170,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pedi" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1087,1170,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">E. pedi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1176,1349,1089,1115]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[188,299,1125,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tsonga" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[188,299,1125,1150]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">E. tsonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[307,486,1124,1150]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, apparently on the same host plant.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
